## 1. Purpose
This policy defines how [COMPANY] formally accepts (retains) information security risk that it has chosen not to fully mitigate, transfer, or avoid. It ensures that risk is only accepted **knowingly**, by an authority **empowered** to accept it, with documented justification, a defined **expiry**, and a record that can be evidenced to assessors. Risk acceptance is the controlled exception to treatment — never a way to silently ignore risk.

## 2. Scope
Applies to any decision to retain residual risk within the ISMS scope, including risks affecting PHI, the production SaaS application, [AWS], [Snowflake], and the [GitHub] CI/CD pipeline. It also serves as the underlying mechanism for policy exceptions raised under `../governance/exceptions-and-waivers.md.template`.

## 3. Policy
1. Risk **shall** be accepted only through a documented risk acceptance record approved by an authority empowered for that risk level per §5.
2. No risk acceptance **shall** be open-ended. Every acceptance **shall** carry an **expiry date** and be re-reviewed at or before expiry (§7).
3. The accepting authority **shall** be informed of the risk's likelihood, impact, residual score, the reason mitigation is not being performed, and any compensating controls before accepting.
4. **PHI-related risk** rated High or Critical **shall not** be accepted below the [CEO]/[Privacy Officer] level, and acceptance **shall** consider HIPAA obligations; risk acceptance does **not** waive any regulatory notification or safeguard requirement.
5. Each acceptance **shall** be recorded in the risk acceptance log (§8) and cross-referenced to the corresponding Risk ID in `risk-register.md.template`.
6. Compensating controls relied upon at acceptance **shall** be documented and monitored for the duration of the acceptance.
7. Expired acceptances **shall** automatically lapse; the underlying risk reverts to **Open** and must be re-treated or re-accepted.

## 4. Roles & Responsibilities
| Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| Requestor / Risk Owner | Documents the risk, justification, compensating controls, and proposed expiry; submits for acceptance. |
| [Security Officer / CISO] | Reviews acceptance requests for completeness; maintains the acceptance log; accepts risk within delegated authority. |
| [CTO / CEO] | Accepts High/Critical residual risk per §5. |
| [Privacy Officer] | Co-approves acceptance of PHI-related risk. |

See `../governance/roles-and-responsibilities.md.template`.

## 5. Acceptance Authority by Risk Level
<!-- TEMPLATE: Tailor authorities to your org. Higher residual risk requires higher authority. -->
| Residual Risk Level (per POL-RSK-01) | Who may accept | Max acceptance duration before re-review |
|---|---|---|
| Low (1–4) | [Risk Owner] (notify Security Officer) | [12 months] |
| Moderate (5–9) | [Security Officer] | [12 months] |
| High (10–15) | [Security Officer + CTO] | [6 months] |
| Critical (16–25) | [CTO + CEO] | [3 months] |
| Any PHI-related High/Critical risk | [CEO + Privacy Officer] | [3 months] |

## 6. Required Documentation
Each risk acceptance record **shall** include:
- Risk ID (link to register), description, and residual score (L × I).
- Reason for acceptance (why not mitigate/transfer/avoid).
- Compensating controls in place.
- Accepting authority and date.
- Expiry / mandatory review date.
- Conditions that would force early re-review (e.g., new incident, scope change).

## 7. Expiry & Review
Every acceptance is time-bound per §5. The [Security Officer] tracks expiry dates and re-reviews each acceptance at or before expiry. At review the risk is re-scored and either (a) re-accepted by the appropriate authority, (b) treated, or (c) closed. A triggering event (incident, significant change, regulatory change) forces early re-review regardless of expiry.

